  1. We have seen that in p = 2 dimensions, a linear decision boundary takes the form Î²0 +Î²1X1 +Î²2X2 = 0. We now investigate a non-linear decision boundary.
  1. Sketch the curve (1+X1)2 +(2âX2)2 =4.
  2. On your sketch, indicate the set of points for which (1+X1)2 +(2âX2)2 >4, as well as the set of points for which (1+X1)2 +(2âX2)2 â¤4.
  3. Suppose that a classifier assigns an observation to the blue class if and to the red class otherwise. To what class is the observation (1+X1)2 +(2âX2)2 >4, (0, 0) classified? (â1, 1)? (2, 2)? (3, 8)?
  4. Argue that while the decision boundary in (c) is not linear in terms of X1 and X2, it is linear in terms of X1, X12, X2, and X2 .

Answer (a) the curve is a circle with center (â1,2) and radius 2 (1+X1)2+(2âX2)2=4 (X1â(â1))2+((â1)(X2â2))2=4 (X1â(â1))2+(X2â2)2=2^2

The decision boundary is defined as the boundary where the function f(X) changes its sign. In this case, f(X)=0 represents the boundary because itâs where the prediction changes. \[\begin{align*} f(X) & \Rightarrow f(X) = 0 \\ & = (1 + X_1)^2 + (2 - X_2)^2 - 4 \\ & = X_1^2 + 2X_1 + 1 + X_2^2 - 4X_2 + 4 - 4 \\ & = X_1^2 + X_2^2 + 2X_1 - 4X_2 + 1 \\ & = (1)(X_1^2) + (1)(X_2^2) + (2)(X_1) + (-4)(X_2) + 1 = 0 \end{align*}\] From the final form we can see how f(X)=0 is expressed in the form a1Z1+a2Z2+ a3Z3+a4Z4+b=0 for (Z1,Z2,Z3,Z4)=(X21,X22,X1,X2), and therefore it is linear in terms of x1, x1^2, x2, and x2^2. Thus, the decision boundary is a circle in the feature space.
